    'topic' => ' Average Density of Cargo?',
    'body' => 'I\'m visiting my folks in Maryland, where I have a much easier time finding
nautical books than in Colorado. I picked up a copy of
_Modern_Ship_Stowage_, US Dept of Commerce, 1942. 

Broken stowage is "the waste and loss of space caused by irregularity in
the size and shape of packages or the incidence of hold pillars, frames,
deck beams, and other obstructions."

Broken stowage for various types of cargo (not allowing for filling the
space with smaller goods):

Miscellaneous package freight	10-25%
(average probably 15%)
Standard package freight
	Bales				3-20%
	Sacks				0-12%
	Barrels			10-50%
	Cases				4-20%
	Drums				8-25%
	Rolls				10-25%
	Coils				10-25%
Bulk freight
	Grain				2-10%
	Lumber				5-50%
	Stone				5-10%
	Pig iron; ore			0-20%
	Car material			15-35%
	Locomotive material		10-25%

"It will be noted that broken stowage of 15 percent means that 15 percent
of the hold capacity remains unused because there is lost space between
units of cargo. It is assumed that the space is not filled with goods....
Some of these percentages are unnecessarily high, but are given because
they were provided by the stevedores."

These figures are pre-containerization, but there will be some broken
stowage with containers as well: either the cargo hold is designed for
general cargo and there are corners where containers won\'t fit, or the
cargo hold is designed for containers and there is some waste space where
the shape of the hold doesn\'t quite match the shape of the hull.

There are extensive lists of stowage factors in this book, but the only
generic figure I could find was an estimate of 40 cubic feet per long ton
(2,240 lbs). This works out to 1.11 m3 per metric ton, or 12.6 metric tons
per dton. Clothing packed for shipping in wooden crates is as close as I
could find to general baggage, at 2.90 m3/mton or 4.83 mton/dton. Both
figures do not account for broken stowage.

If someone has specific questions, I\'d be happy to look them up.

Side issue: has anyone (former Air Force loadmasters, maybe?) considered
weight and balance in the design of starships and the stowage of freight?
Specifically: can the use of artificial gravity and/or contragravity
compensate for unbalanced loads -- both design loads and cargo -- and if
so, how? 
